  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are international laws and frameworks designed to combat money laundering. These laws are established through various international organizations and agreements to ensure a coordinated global effort in fighting financial crimes. Some of the key international frameworks and laws include:\n\n1. **United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (Palermo Convention)**  \n   - This convention, adopted in 2000, includes provisions to combat money laundering as part of efforts to address organized crime globally.\n\n2. **United Nations Convention against Corruption (UNCAC)**  \n   - Adopted in 2003, UNCAC requires member states to implement anti-money laundering measures and strengthen international cooperation to prevent and combat corruption-related money laundering.\n\n3. **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)**  \n   - FATF is an intergovernmental organization established in 1989 to set international standards for combating money laundering, terrorist financing, and other related threats. Its **FATF Recommendations** (also known as the 40 Recommendations) are the global standard for anti-money laundering (AML) and counter-terrorist financing (CFT) measures.\n\n4. **Basel Committee on Banking Supervision**  \n   - The committee, part of the Bank for International Settlements, has issued guidelines for banks to prevent money laundering, particularly through its **Basel AML Principles**.\n\n5. **European Union Directives on Money Laundering**  \n   - The EU has implemented a series of Anti-Money Laundering Directives (AMLD) that require member states to adopt strict AML measures. The **6th Anti-Money Laundering Directive (6AMLD)**, effective from 2020, strengthened penalties and expanded the scope of money laundering offenses.\n\n6. **International Monetary Fund (IMF) and World Bank**  \n   - These institutions provide technical assistance and support to countries in implementing AML/CFT measures and assessing compliance with international standards.\n\nThese international laws and frameworks are complemented by national legislation in individual countries, which implement the agreed-upon standards and adapt them to local contexts. Compliance with these laws is monitored through peer reviews, mutual evaluations, and reporting mechanisms.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
